      <div id="block-1-expanded" class="block-expanded">
        <img src="images/ADM-176-121.jpg" alt="HM Carnavon (ADM 176/121)" title="HM Carnavon (ADM 176/121)"/>
        <div class="img-desc">Admiralty ship Carnavon launched (<a href="https://images.nationalarchives.gov.uk/assetbank-nationalarchives/action/viewAsset?id=10969&amp;index=0&amp;total=1&amp;view=viewSearchItem" target="_blank">ADM 176/121</a>)</div>
        
        <h2>The Battle of the Falkland Islands</h2>
        <div class="content-scroll cscroll">
          <p>Following the defeat of British ships by the Germans at the Battle of Coronel in early November, on 8th December 1914, the Battle of the Falkland Islands took place. HM Ships Invincible, Inflexible, Carnavon, Cornwall, Kent, Glasgow and Bristol, arrived at Port Stanley under the direction of Vice-Admiral Sturdee to join Macedonia and Canopus early on 7th December 1914 (<a href="http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/SearchUI/Details?uri=C2488554" target="_blank">ADM 186/591</a>). The following morning, German ships commanded by Admiral Maximilian Spee were sighted. A fierce battle ensued with many hundreds of German casualities, prisoners and the loss of the Scharnhost, Gneisenau, Nurnberg and Leipsic. There were a small number of British casualties and a number of British men were honoured for their actions (<a href="http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/SearchUI/Details?uri=C4491607" target="_blank">CO 323/686</a>).</p>
          <p> Sergeant Charles Mayes, no. 3307, was awarded the Conspicuous Gallantry Medal for his actions aboard HMS Kent. He extinguished a fire near live ammunition which "saved a disaster which might have led to the loss of the ship." (<a href="http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/SearchUI/Details?uri=C4491607" target="_blank">CO 323/686</a>) </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div id="block-2-expanded" class="block-expanded">
        <img src="images/RAIL-253-516-1915.jpg" alt="Postcard from Pte H Giles  (RAIL-253-516-1915)" title="Postcard from Pte H Giles  (RAIL-253-516-1915)"/>
        <div class="img-desc">Postcard from Pte H Giles  (<a href="https://images.nationalarchives.gov.uk/assetbank-nationalarchives/action/viewAsset?id=31958&amp;index=107&amp;total=113&amp;view=viewSearchItem" target="_blank">RAIL-253-516-1915</a>)</div>
        
        <h2>Falkland Island Volunteers</h2>
        <div class="content-scroll cscroll">
          <p>On 16th August 1914, almost immediately after the declaration of war, William Allardyce, Governor of the Falklands, issued a proclamation that all Officers and Volunteers from the Falkland Islands Volunteer Corps should meet and be prepared to report for duty  (<a href="http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/SearchUI/Details?uri=C2515022" target="_blank">CO 458/5</a>).</p>
          <p>The Falklands Volunteer Corps were never involved in direct fighting, although they were recommended for honours by Governor Allardyce for their preparations and actions as lookouts and wireless operators during the Battle of the Falkland Islands (<a href="http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/SearchUI/Details?uri=C9275893" target="_blank">CO 23/278/12</a>).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
